				<a name="1268433"></a><img border="0" class="blogs_anonicon" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://images.ittoolbox.com/vt/icons/postreply.png" alt="comment"/><div class="blog_commentorname"><b>MikeVx </b> writes:</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					12/7/2006&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1268433" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				I would pin modules as the culprit here.  In theory, Linux modules are a wonderful idea, in practice, they are sanity-shredding nightmares.  Depending on machine startup variations, network traffic bouncing of the NIC, the temperature of the room and the phase of the moon, modules will do less-than-predictable things.  If modules do not block further boot processing until they finish initializing, I can see where one disk being a slow starter due to a chilly room could change completion order.

I never use a module unless there is no means of getting the support compiled directly into the kernel, and then I must need the function the module supports pretty badly to put myself through the havoc that always follows. (I've had very bad experiences with modules, can you tell?)

I compile support for all drive controllers (and everything else I need, for that matter) into the kernel.  This results in the drivers always loading in the same order, and the drives always getting the same device IDs.  If I add/remove/change a controller this can change the IDs, once per controller add/remove/change.  I fix the mountings and get on with life.

"If you need consistent device IDs, Mr. Module is no longer your friend."
(This may not be true, but the quote started bouncing around in my head and I had to write down.)


