				<a name="1268803"></a><img border="0" class="blogs_anonicon" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://images.ittoolbox.com/vt/icons/postreply.png" alt="comment"/><div class="blog_commentorname"><b>Kaos </b> writes:</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					12/8/2006&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1268803" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				I havnt been back here in a while.

When you install slackware or gentoo its all manual, lebeling is the users responsibility as well as partitioning...its not all handled by a gui like most other distros.

depending on the skill level of the person performing the install you can have any number of partitions one for /home one for /var one for /boot a regular ol root partition...you name it. /hd1a /hd1b ... havnt used gentoo in forever so i cant remember if theyre using the bsd moniker or the traditional linux style.

lets say you have a flash drive and you put a record in your fstab so that udev or hotplug always has a reference as to where to mount it..and this was set up before the SAN and your mountpoints are the actual hdx points..you could easily haveone thing where you think the other is.

in regards to "how they are found"...well it could have to do with different hardware configurations, flash drives, how fast one machine hits the SAN over the network vs the other.

Also smaller labs/offices tend not to have standardized hardware for the users' desktop systems...sometimes the network topology looks like it was designed by a 5 year old playing "connect the dots"

dont quote me as a genius on this stuff, I only mess with linux barely at work and ive only been a linux user at home (although I am %100 linux at home now) for about 9 months now.


