				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				I am definitely not a "Linux wonk", but I've enjoyed this case file immensely. As a Infosec professional in training, I enjoy parsing out what I can based on my limited knowledge, and learning from what others reply with. Definitely in agreement with the Chief here - if anyone can put things in focus, please do so! I use these articles as an educational resource as well as a source of enjoyable reading ^_^ I'm sure I'd not be the only one benefiting from the shared knowledge.

I think a lot of people got the wrong idea about how you approached the idea of challenging the more Linux-savvy readers of the blog. The article is plenty enjoyable even for those who don't understand the technical details, right? I didn't take this post as a downer on those who don't know those things, but a challenge to those who do. People from a wide range of backgrounds read this blog, not everyone's going to get every post. So let the pleasure readers read for pleasure, and let the challenge-seekers enjoy the challenge. To each their own, right?


			</div>
		</div><div class="blogs_commententry">
			<div>
				<a name="1273859"></a><img border="0" id="4_1273859" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/0/0/0/t_610000.jpg" class="members_badgeSmall" alt="Security Monkey" badgeentityid="610000"/><div class="blog_commentorname">
					<b><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/people/chiefmonkey/">Security Monkey</a></b> writes:
				</div><div>

				</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					12/12/2006&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1273859" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				Kaos:

You are exactly right.  It's all about mount order - what the kernel/modules find, and WHEN they find them.  Your example of the flash drive is a great example.

Chief


			</div>
		</div><div class="blogs_commententry">
			<div>
				<a name="1421256"></a><img border="0" class="blogs_anonicon" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://images.ittoolbox.com/vt/icons/postreply.png" alt="comment"/><div class="blog_commentorname"><b>IceWolf </b> writes:</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					4/24/2007&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1421256" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				There are a number of holes in this story Chief.<br><br>A) SAN volumes presented to more than one host simultaneously? Unless those hosts are clustered, how is locking controlled. We assume no persistent SCSI reservations?<br><br>B) SAN volume presentation is discretionary, in this case I would have to assume (and I hate assumptions) that the SAN volumes were presented in the same order to both workstations and that A was not a factor assuming that two workstations would not be accessing the same LUN at the same time.<br><br>C) Gentoo, when installed, is usually recompiled on the machine, to ensure maximum performance, which means any variance in hardware will result in variances in the way the kernel and modules are built on the machines.<br><br>D) We also have to assume the filesystem formats on the SAN volumes are something that does not support volume tagging or labelling. Which is odd, since with Gentoo, the default would probably be ext3 (Extended Filesystem version 3) which supports volume tagging, which would help prevent users from mounting the wrong volume.<br><br>So without matching the WWID's of the indivudual LUNs presented from the SAN on each workstation, or checking the configuration of the storage array as to the order in which devies are presented where, there is no guarantee that you are looking at the same device in two locations and I certainly would not expect a storage vendor to configure an array like that.<br><br>Overall it was a moot point, but since you posed the additional queries regarding devices.<br><br>- Ice



			</div>
		</div><div class="blogs_commententry">
			<div>
				<a name="1526920"></a><img border="0" class="blogs_anonicon" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://images.ittoolbox.com/vt/icons/postreply.png" alt="comment"/><div class="blog_commentorname"><b>seldon </b> writes:</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					7/15/2007&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1526920" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				This does not only apply to hard disks, but essentially to all devices that you have two or more of. Well, except IDE drives, those are allocated by bus order :P<br><br>However, with the advent of udev, that problem has become solvable - it allows you to assign device node names dependent  on unique hardware specs, such as MAC addresses for ethernet cards. I do that on laptops with the lan, wlan and winmodem adapters, because kernel updates sometimes screwed up my wpa_supplicant config. Heh. <br><br>Anyway, it's a very flexible system. It works easiest with stuff that's exported to /sys, but you can also hook it up to other programs, such as, say, scsi_id, and assign names based on that.



			</div>
		</div><div class="blogs_commententry">
			<div>
				<a name="1537890"></a><img border="0" id="4_1537890" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/t_icon.jpg" class="members_badgeSmall" alt="gliderguider" badgeentityid="1143604"/><div class="blog_commentorname">
					<b><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/people/gliderguider/">gliderguider</a></b> writes:
				</div><div>

				</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					7/22/2007&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1537890" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				I find it strange that it is assumed that devices on the SAN are presented to more than one system at the same time.  While it may have been intended to be used that way, I find it a bit unusual.  Most filesystem drivers presume that they have exclusive access to the volume.  Imagine system A doing a write to a file while another does the same to the same file.  Each system assumes that what is sitting in its read cache is what it just wrote to the disk.<br><br>There are a few environments with various clustering services (HP MC ServiceGuard) where more than one system will have access to the same volumes on the SAN.  In this case there is intersystem communication to make sure that only one system has a volume mounted at a time.<br><br>Most large scale SANs allow you to present different volumes or LUNs to different hosts normally emulating SCSI devices.  It would be normal for most systems to only see a small percentage of the SAN.  Due to the limited number of SCSI addresses available to any one system, I can present one LUN to one system with a given SCSI ID/lun ID and another LUN to a different system with the same SCSI ID/lun ID.  <br><br>For data security purposes, there is usually some sort of LUN security that only allows a system to see the LUNS that it is allowed to have access to.  Without this security, you need some very careful configuration to make sure that data chaos doesn't reign.<br><br>Gliderguider<br><br>



			</div>
		</div><div class="blogs_commententry">
			<div>
				<a name="1552187"></a><img border="0" class="blogs_anonicon" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://images.ittoolbox.com/vt/icons/postreply.png" alt="comment"/><div class="blog_commentorname"><b>Caimlas </b> writes:</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					8/1/2007&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#1552187" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				It would appear to me that the mount order may have been attributed to the existence of the USB key drive. <br><br>USB CF drives typically get assigned an sdx device name, and depending on how the modules were loaded, it could have been that the USB drive was getting assigned /dev/sda, while the SAN drives then got loaded sequentially afterwards. This may have been why the researcher did not us fstab to mount the san drives (he knew enough to remove their automatic entry from fstab but not enough to correct the matter, maybe). This wasn't too clear to me - or the particulars as to why the boss was the one having problems. <br><br>This may simply due to never personally having a problem with network devices mounting as they should, but it might also be due to the explanation (or omission thereof). There are a couple questions still in my mind, such as why the boss's system was mounting things in the wrong/a different order. Who set the systems up? If it was the researcher, he may have set the boss's system up without the foreknowledge of the sda USB CF - and the boss simply never looked at the files on the SAN (though that's not too likely).<br><br>(God damn it I wish modules.conf was used as it used to be used - as a sequentially read reference for module load order. For that matter, I'm not too fond of hotplug for anything system-side for this very reason...)



			</div>
		</div><div class="blogs_commententry">
			<div>
				<a name="2121503"></a><img border="0" class="blogs_anonicon" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931im_/http://images.ittoolbox.com/vt/icons/postreply.png" alt="comment"/><div class="blog_commentorname"><b>David Comeau </b> writes:</div><div class="blogs_anchor">
					5/20/2008&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100710090931/http://it.toolbox.com/blogs/securitymonkey/case-of-the-heaping-haystack-redux-13342#2121503" class="hoverM">#</a>
				</div>
			</div><div class="blogs_commententrybody">
				
once again, i know that this is old, but the issue that had developed due to the SAN can be solved by mounting by volume label or by filesystem UUID, instead of by block device name.<br><br>this particular problem rears its ugly head when you have two drive controllers in the same box, and the order of detection is absolutely random.  we call it a "race condition".  whichever one finishes first gets the device allocation.<br><br>yeah, udev takes care of a good chunk of this nowadays, but not every machine's the same, and you're particularly out of luck if when udev first takes a profile of the machine layout, that it identified the SAN wrong on that first boot.  you're only chances of guaranteed success is if you go and duplicate one workstation's "persistent rules" onto another, thereby having deployed the same udev profile across multiple system.<br><br>hence, why i normally go by filesystem UUID.


			</div>
		</div></td>
